summary: Isn't Jaqen too old for Arya ? Gendry is closer in age to her
question: Isn't Jaqen too old for Arya ? Gendry is closer in age to her
answer:
Book spoilers

Bookwise Jaqen is 18 years old. The age gap between Jaqen, Arya and Gendry is the same as between Rhaegar, Lyanna and Robert. In Westeros “a man grown” is a boy as young as 16 years old, that’s why Gendry is often described as “almost a man” or “the closest thing to a man.” Jaqen refers to himself as “a man” like Loras does but Jaime thinks Loras is still a boy. The same goes for Jon, Sam and Pate. Technically they all are “the men grown” but they are still teenagers. GRRM gives away Pate’s age in A Feast for Crows to let us know how old Jaqen is.

In the show we are talking about two grown up actors performing their roles not actual people starting a relationship. Usually actors portray characters younger than themselves. In many high school themed shows/movies the main characters are played by the actors well in their twenties. We can assume that in the show Jaqen is a seasoned assassin who may fall for a young but adult apprentice. Arya is a grown up girl in the show and so is Maisie. I don’t see anything wrong about it as long as the relationship is consensual and people involved are adults. 

Thank you for the question :)

summary:
Ugh, the misrepresentation and double standards surrounding Arya annoy me greatly.  
Arya Stark is NOT a killer. She's not an...
body:
Ugh, the misrepresentation and double standards surrounding Arya annoy me greatly.

Arya Stark is NOT a killer. She’s not an assassin. Her ONLY goal is to take out those who have definitively hurt/killed those she cares about. Those who have done a horrible injustice. So she’s not going to kill people just for… reasons. The show (and GRRM in the books) made this so clear if one would just pay attention instead of focusing on girl with pointy sword who kills!

- That’s why she didn’t kill anyone the May Faced God ordered her to kill if they didn’t deserve it (in the books or on the show).

- She was not going to kill the Frey women who were innocent. Or the Freys who were not a part of the Red Wedding slaughter. That’s why we specifically we’re told that she gathered the Frey men who were involved in the Red Wedding.

- That’s why we were shown Arya interacting with Lannister soldiers and NOT killing them.

- That’s why we were shown Arya choosing Winterfell/family over her list/killing Cersei.

Arya Stark is not morally corrupt. She’s not an assassin. Or a ruthless, black-hearted killer. She’s a moralist who’s only goal is to protect her family/those she loves and exact justice against those who have done others wrong. She’s a warrior; she just happens to be a warrior with many dangerous skills who is also a teenage girl with a pointy sword who has a high kill count. She is also following the moral code that Ned Stark, and the Starks of Winterfell have followed for centuries. The same as Jon Snow, the same as Robb Stark. She just happens to be a female Stark.

summary: I was thinking about something that might be of importance for the possibility of a Gendrya romance. Right now Gendry and Arya...
body: I was thinking about something that might be of importance for the possibility of a Gendrya romance. Right now Gendry and Arya have no significant other whether that be a close friend or a love interest. They are both alone. Arya is with her family and Gendry is with Davos who is like a father to him but apart from that they currently have no one in their lives. Even though they both could’ve made new connections, Arya in Braavos and Gendry in Kings Landing. We know Arya did not have any close friends or a love interest in Braavos, she was lonely. We can’t know if Gendry has someone but considering the fact that he immediately left his place the minute Davos showed up tells us he has no one worth staying for which is strange because lbr he is handsome and is successful in his job, I’m sure he would have some admirers. But the writers made a point of showing Gendry completely alone and being ready to leave. And even in s7 they made no deep connection to other characters, Arya didn’t really interact with the people in Winterfell other than Sansa and Gendry befriended Jon but it remained shallow. That makes the bond between Gendry and Arya stronger and more significant since they both didn’t really find a new friend or a romantic partner. If that had been the case the possibility of a romance would’ve been low. The fact that they will enter s8 without any deep and developed relationship (apart from Arya’s family and Davos) could mean that they will be pretty important to each other. They are both alone and they don’t know that they will see each other again. I mean think about it. It’s kind of weird but if the writes wanted to make a romance between them it would make sense. What’s your take on that?
